      "writtenOn": "2018-09-20T01:02:09Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "If setUp fails, Func and cleanupFunc shouldn\u0027t run?",
      "revId": "197c8e2bb80a3cf2bcc3e9183314a9f067f6381e",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f89ae5a9_ac46b48c",
        "filename": "src/chromiumos/tast/testing/test.go",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 111,
      "author": {
        "id": 1118346
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-20T02:07:24Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I have a different opinion here --- cleanupFunc should run even if setupFunc panicked.\n\nLet\u0027s think about this scenario: setupFunc does initialization of three components: A, B, C in this order, and cleanupFunc does de-initialization of C, B, A. If setupFunc panicked during initializing B, we somehow need to de-initialize A. The idiomatic way in this case is to run cleanupFunc (after making it capable of handling non-initialized B/C). Otherwise we need to include de-initialization of A in setupFunc, which is totally duplicated with part of cleanupFunc.",
      "parentUuid": "1300b1c6_7ca92a0c",
      "revId": "197c8e2bb80a3cf2bcc3e9183314a9f067f6381e",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c2e04595_d106084e",
        "filename": "src/chromiumos/tast/testing/test.go",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 111,
      "author": {
        "id": 1115919
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-20T02:19:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Otherwise we need to include de-initialization of A in setupFunc, which is totally duplicated with part of cleanupFunc.\n\nI think it should be in general, unfortunately (though I\u0027m not a big fun of the code dup).\nGo\u0027s defer approach is, calling tearing-down method if and only if initialization succeeds.\n(Note that this is not only for go, but also in other langs. E.g. in c++, if an exception is raised in ctor, dtor won\u0027t run).\nI think it\u0027s better to follow the approach.\n\nAlso, in any case, I don\u0027t think Func should run.",
      "parentUuid": "f89ae5a9_ac46b48c",
      "revId": "197c8e2bb80a3cf2bcc3e9183314a9f067f6381e",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
